<section id="job">
  <h2>What job should the homepage do?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">A homepage is the front door and the main routing point of a website. Its job is not to tell the entire company story. It should help a new visitor recognise that they are in the right place, understand the value, find the most relevant route and feel confident enough to continue.</p>
  <p>That sounds simple, but most homepages are trying to serve several audiences at once. A referral may arrive looking for reassurance. A search visitor may be comparing services. A returning prospect may want proof or contact details. An existing customer may need support. The homepage needs to prioritise without pretending every visitor has the same intent.</p>
  <p>Start with the commercial job, not a list of sections. Define the primary action that matters, the visitors most likely to take it and the questions preventing them from doing so. A service business may need qualified enquiries. An ecommerce brand may need visitors to reach the right collection. A complex B2B company may need buyers to understand an unfamiliar offer before they will speak to sales.</p>
  <div class="article-callout">
    <span>Working principle</span>
    <p><strong>Order the homepage around the buyer's questions:</strong> Am I in the right place? Is this relevant to me? Why should I trust this company? What can I do next?</p>
  </div>
  <p>This is why a homepage and a landing page are different. A campaign landing page can serve one audience, one promise and one action. A homepage normally has to orient several types of visitor while keeping one commercial priority clear. If the page tries to become a landing page for every service and keyword, it usually becomes repetitive and difficult to scan.</p>
</section>

<section id="above-fold">
  <h2>What belongs above the fold?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">The first screen should make the category, audience, value and next step understandable without requiring the visitor to decode a slogan. It does not need to complete the sale, but it should earn the next scroll or click.</p>
  <h3>A clear, descriptive H1</h3>
  <p>The main heading should explain what the business offers in language a customer would recognise. A distinctive line can still work, but the supporting copy must remove ambiguity. Avoid leading with an internal mission, a vague superlative or a statement that could belong to almost any competitor.</p>
  <h3>A supporting proposition</h3>
  <p>Use one or two short sentences to add the audience, outcome, location or important difference. This is where a Manchester service business can make its coverage clear, a retailer can explain its product position, or a specialist B2B provider can describe the problem it solves.</p>
  <h3>One primary action and one useful alternative</h3>
  <p>The primary call to action should reflect realistic visitor readiness. “Buy now” can suit a simple product. “Request an audit” or “Submit a project” may suit a considered service. A secondary route such as viewing work can support visitors who need evidence first. Several buttons are acceptable when they maintain a clear hierarchy. Several equally loud priorities are not.</p>
  <h3>Immediate relevance or proof</h3>
  <p>Depending on the sale, the first screen can include a client name, review signal, credential, outcome or visual example. It should support the promise rather than compete with it. Never place an impressive number in the hero unless its meaning, period and evidence can be explained.</p>
  <div class="article-callout article-callout--dark">
    <span>Do not design to a mythical fold</span>
    <p>Screen height changes across devices and browser settings. Treat the first viewport as the beginning of a coherent sequence, not a rigid box that must contain navigation, five claims, every service, three badges and a form.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="structure">
  <h2>A practical homepage structure that supports conversion</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">There is no universal number of sections. The following sequence is a useful starting point because it moves from orientation to relevance, evidence and action. Remove or reorder anything that does not serve the actual buyer.</p>
  <div class="article-framework">
    <article><div><span>01</span><h3>Header and routes</h3></div><p>Keep the main navigation predictable and make the highest-value destinations easy to reach. Do not hide essential routes behind clever labels.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>02</span><h3>Hero proposition</h3></div><p>State the offer, audience or outcome clearly, then show the primary next step and a lower-commitment route where useful.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>03</span><h3>Fast relevance</h3></div><p>Let visitors self-select by service, problem, product category, sector or location before they have to read a long company narrative.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>04</span><h3>Value and difference</h3></div><p>Explain why the approach is useful. Translate capabilities into the progress a buyer needs, while avoiding unsupported superiority claims.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>05</span><h3>Proof in context</h3></div><p>Connect testimonials, examples, results and credentials to the claim they support instead of placing every trust signal in one logo wall.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>06</span><h3>Offer or service system</h3></div><p>Show the core routes with enough detail to help a visitor choose. Use descriptive links that make the destination clear.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>07</span><h3>Selected work</h3></div><p>Show the situation, work and verified outcome. A relevant case study is stronger than a large gallery with no commercial context.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>08</span><h3>How it works</h3></div><p>Reduce uncertainty by explaining the first conversation, likely process, ownership and what the customer should prepare.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>09</span><h3>Objections and details</h3></div><p>Answer questions about fit, timing, investment, support or risk when those answers help a buyer decide whether to continue.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>10</span><h3>Focused close</h3></div><p>Repeat the next step with useful context. The final CTA should feel like the logical continuation of the page, not a generic sales banner.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>11</span><h3>Useful footer</h3></div><p>Include contact, legal and key navigation information. The footer is part of the journey, particularly for trust-sensitive purchases.</p></article>
  </div>
  <p>The navigation and service links also help search engines understand the site. Google recommends crawlable HTML links and descriptive anchor text, and says every important page should be linked from at least one other page. That does not mean filling the homepage with exact-match keywords. It means naming destinations naturally and making the site structure usable. See <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/crawling-indexing/links-crawlable">Google's link best practices</a>.</p>
</section>

<section id="business-models">
  <h2>How should the structure change by business model?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">The same generic wireframe should not be applied to a local service, an ecommerce catalogue and a high-consideration B2B offer. The buyer's first task changes, so the emphasis and order should change too.</p>
  <div class="article-table-wrap">
    <table class="article-table">
      <caption>Homepage priorities by business model</caption>
      <thead><tr><th>Business model</th><th>Primary homepage job</th><th>Bring forward</th><th>Common mistake</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Local service business</td><td>Confirm service, coverage and trust, then create a suitable enquiry.</td><td>Locations, availability, credentials, reviews and a clear booking or enquiry route.</td><td>Leading with a long founder story before explaining the service and area.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Considered B2B service</td><td>Help several stakeholders understand relevance and reduce perceived risk.</td><td>Problems solved, sectors, approach, case studies and clear expectations for the first step.</td><td>Using abstract brand language that requires insider knowledge to understand.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Ecommerce</td><td>Move customers into relevant products or collections with confidence.</td><td>Category routes, search, merchandising, delivery, returns and product reassurance.</td><td>Treating the page as one large campaign poster with poor product discovery.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>New business or startup</td><td>Establish clarity and credibility when historic proof is limited.</td><td>Founder expertise, transparent process, product demonstration and honest early evidence.</td><td>Inventing scale through stock logos, vague counters or unverified testimonials.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>CNVRT's <a href="/work/hear-better/">Hear Better work</a> is a useful service-business example. The site needed to explain mobile audiology, earn trust from an older audience and build routes into services and locations. By contrast, Heatons Furniture needed product discovery, merchandising and reassurance around high-value ecommerce purchases. Those are different homepage problems even though both need clarity, proof and action.</p>
</section>

<section id="proof">
  <h2>Where should proof appear on a homepage?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">Place proof close to the claim it supports. A testimonial about communication belongs near the process. A commercial result belongs near the related case study. A professional credential belongs near the specialist service it validates.</p>
  <p>A long logo strip can create recognition, but it rarely explains what work was completed. Use a smaller number of relevant examples with context: the starting position, the decision CNVRT made, what was delivered and which result has been verified.</p>
  <h3>Build a hierarchy of evidence</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Specific project evidence:</strong> a relevant case study with scope, decisions and an approved outcome.</li>
    <li><strong>Named client perspective:</strong> a signed testimonial that describes the experience and useful change.</li>
    <li><strong>External validation:</strong> reviews, platform status or certifications that are current and accurately described.</li>
    <li><strong>Process evidence:</strong> screenshots, deliverables, frameworks and explanations that show how the work is done.</li>
    <li><strong>General reassurance:</strong> response time, support model, ownership and clearly stated commercial boundaries.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Proof should be selective. An unrelated ecommerce result should not be used to sell a local healthcare website simply because the number is larger. Relevance usually creates more confidence than volume.</p>
</section>

<section id="mistakes">
  <h2>Common homepage mistakes that weaken conversion</h2>
  <h3>The message is distinctive but not understandable</h3>
  <p>Brand voice matters, but a new visitor should not need to interpret a metaphor before learning what the company does. Pair the distinctive idea with clear category and audience language.</p>
  <h3>Every internal stakeholder gets a section</h3>
  <p>A homepage built by committee often becomes a stack of disconnected priorities. Give each proposed section a job in the customer decision. If it cannot earn attention, establish relevance, answer an objection or support action, move it to a more appropriate page.</p>
  <h3>The page asks for commitment before earning trust</h3>
  <p>A high-consideration service may need work examples, approach and fit information before a booking request feels reasonable. Add a secondary route for visitors who are not ready, but avoid turning the page into a maze of weak actions.</p>
  <h3>Testimonials are anonymous or too polished</h3>
  <p>“Great service, highly recommended” adds little. A strong testimonial names the person, their role, the situation and the practical difference, with permission to publish.</p>
  <h3>Animation controls the reading experience</h3>
  <p>Motion can show hierarchy and make transitions feel considered. It should not delay important text, hijack scrolling or become the only way to understand a sequence. Respect reduced-motion preferences and make the full journey usable without animation.</p>
  <h3>The homepage tries to rank for every service</h3>
  <p>The homepage should introduce the business and route people to substantial service pages. Repeating every keyword variation creates poor copy and blurs page ownership. A connected architecture is more useful than one overloaded page.</p>
</section>

<section id="mobile-accessibility">
  <h2>Mobile, speed and accessibility are part of the structure</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">A conversion-focused homepage is not finished when the desktop composition looks good. The order, labels, tap targets, forms, images and movement must remain understandable across different screens and methods of navigation.</p>
  <p>The W3C explains that well-structured content helps people navigate and process a page, and recommends meaningful regions with headings nested according to their relationships. This supports screen-reader, keyboard and mobile-reader navigation. See the <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/tutorials/page-structure/">W3C page structure tutorial</a>.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep one H1 and use descriptive H2 and H3 headings to expose the page hierarchy.</li>
    <li>Ensure primary actions meet comfortable tap-target sizes and have clear focus states.</li>
    <li>Do not rely on hover to reveal essential information.</li>
    <li>Write useful alt text for informative images and leave decorative images empty.</li>
    <li>Keep forms short enough for the actual qualification task and label every field.</li>
    <li>Reserve image space to prevent layout movement and compress large media.</li>
    <li>Check that line lengths, type sizes and contrast remain comfortable at 200% zoom.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Speed matters because a delayed or unstable first experience reduces the chance that visitors will reach the useful content. It is still not a substitute for a clear offer. Treat performance, accessibility and message quality as one experience rather than three independent audits.</p>
</section>

<section id="measure">
  <h2>How do you measure whether a homepage converts?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">Do not judge a homepage only by its site-wide form rate. Define the journey it is meant to support, measure the meaningful steps and review the quality of the enquiries or sales created.</p>
  <div class="article-table-wrap">
    <table class="article-table">
      <caption>A useful homepage measurement plan</caption>
      <thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>Useful evidence</th><th>What to investigate</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Do visitors understand where to go?</td><td>Service, collection and case-study click-through by entry source and device.</td><td>Weak labels, missing routes or content placed in the wrong order.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Do they reach the commercial action?</td><td>CTA clicks, form starts, bookings, calls or product discovery events.</td><td>A mismatch between promise, proof and the commitment requested.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Do they complete it?</td><td>Form completion, checkout progression and field-level abandonment.</td><td>Technical errors, unclear expectations, excessive fields or poor mobile usability.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Are the outcomes valuable?</td><td>Qualified leads, booked work, revenue, margin and sales feedback.</td><td>Traffic quality, qualification, offer fit and misleading messaging.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>A test needs a clear hypothesis and enough data to interpret responsibly. Changing three sections, the CTA, the form and the traffic mix together may improve the result, but it will not tell you which decision mattered. CNVRT's <a href="/services/analytics-conversion-tracking/">analytics and conversion tracking work</a> defines the events and commercial feedback needed before design changes are treated as evidence.</p>
</section>

<section id="checklist">
  <h2>Homepage audit checklist</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">Use this as a planning tool, not a universal scoring system. A section is successful when it helps the intended visitor make progress.</p>
  <ul class="article-checklist">
    <li>The H1 identifies the offer or outcome in language a customer recognises.</li>
    <li>The supporting copy clarifies audience, location or an important difference.</li>
    <li>The primary action matches realistic visitor readiness.</li>
    <li>A lower-commitment route exists where buyers normally need evidence first.</li>
    <li>Navigation labels describe their destinations and all important pages are linked.</li>
    <li>Visitors can identify the most relevant service, product or problem route quickly.</li>
    <li>Claims are supported by relevant, approved evidence close to the claim.</li>
    <li>The page explains what happens after the visitor takes action.</li>
    <li>Objections are answered without duplicating entire service pages.</li>
    <li>The mobile order remains logical and all controls work without hover.</li>
    <li>Headings are descriptive and nested in a meaningful hierarchy.</li>
    <li>Images are optimised, stable and useful rather than decorative filler.</li>
    <li>Key interactions and completed commercial outcomes are measured.</li>
    <li>Lead quality or revenue is reviewed alongside onsite conversion.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="article-field-note">
    <span>CNVRT field note</span>
    <h3>Begin with the decision, then design the page.</h3>
    <p>CNVRT's <a href="/services/web-design/">web design process</a> begins with the customer, offer, evidence and commercial action. That produces a more useful homepage brief than choosing a visual style and filling a predetermined stack of sections.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="questions">
  <h2>Frequently asked homepage questions</h2>
  <div class="article-questions">
    <details><summary>How many sections should a homepage have?</summary><p>There is no reliable universal number. Use enough sections to establish relevance, explain the offer, provide appropriate evidence and support the next step. A simple local service may need fewer than a complex B2B proposition. Remove sections that repeat another page or do not help the decision.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How long should homepage copy be?</summary><p>Long enough to make the first decision without turning the homepage into every service page. Clear headings, short supporting paragraphs and descriptive links can provide depth without one uninterrupted block of copy. Do not write to a word count.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Should a homepage use one call to action?</summary><p>It should have one clear commercial priority. A secondary action can help visitors who need more proof or have a different valid task. Keep the hierarchy obvious and avoid presenting several equally important next steps.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Should prices appear on the homepage?</summary><p>Include pricing when it helps customers self-qualify and the figure can be stated accurately. For variable projects, a truthful starting point or explanation of cost drivers may be more useful than a misleading fixed price.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Should there be a contact form on the homepage?</summary><p>Only when the request is simple enough for a short form and visitors have received enough context to use it. A dedicated enquiry page can provide clearer expectations and qualification for complex work.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Should the homepage target an SEO keyword?</summary><p>It should have a clear search role that matches the business proposition, but it should not repeat a keyword mechanically. Let specialist service pages own more specific intent and connect them through descriptive navigation and contextual links.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How often should a homepage be updated?</summary><p>Review it when the offer, audience, evidence or customer journey changes, and use performance and sales feedback to prioritise improvements. Do not change the page simply to create a fresh date.</p></details>
  </div>
</section>

